Purely random data
------------------

We first generate the data as Gaussian white noise.

    set.seed(1)
    x <- rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1)

We can then plot the data ..

    plot(x, type="l", col=2, xlab="", ylab="", main="Time Series")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />
... and the autocorrelation function.

    acf(x, lag=25, main="Autocorrelation function")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />

Data with a trend
-----------------

We first generate the data and plot it.

    set.seed(2)
    time <- 1:100
    x <- -0.1*time + rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1)
    plot(x, type="l", col=2, xlab="", ylab="", main="Time Series")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />
We can then generate the autocorrelation function.

    acf(x, lag=25, main="Autocorrelation function")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />
The linear trend leads to a very slowly decaying autocorrelation
function.

Data with a seasonal effect
---------------------------

We first generate data with a seasonal, in our case cosine, component
and plot it

    set.seed(3)
    time <- 1:100
    seasonal <- 2*cos(time/(0.5*pi)/12*10)
    x <- seasonal + rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1)
    plot(x, type="l", col=2, xlab="", ylab="", main="Time Series")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />
The autocorrelation function now shows a peak at the period (12) of the
seasonal effect.

    acf(x, lag=25, main="Autocorrelation function")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />

Data with a trend and a seasonal effect
---------------------------------------

We finally add both a trend and seasonal component to the simulated time
series.

    set.seed(4)
    time <- 1:100
    seasonal <- 2*cos(time/(0.5*pi)/12*10)
    x <- seasonal + rnorm(100, mean=0, sd=1) + 0.1*time
    plot(x, type="l", col=2, xlab="", ylab="", main="Time Series")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />
The autocorrelation function now shows both a slow decay and an
additional peak at 12 corresponding to the period of the seasonal
effect.

    acf(x, lag=25, main="Autocorrelation function")

<img src="data:image/png;base64," width=".45\textwidth" />
